# Impact Dashboard — Product Requirements Document
**Agentic Handoff Format · v5.0**
Theory of Change Reporting · Executive Director & Head of Fundraising

| Field | Value |
|---|---|
| Status | Draft v5.0 — incorporates third third-party critique, June 2026 |
| Org | 20-person, ~$3M Canadian nonprofit |
| Fiscal year | January 1 – December 31 |

---

## 1. What to Build

A private web app for a single small nonprofit where staff manually enter program outcome data, fundraising revenue, and funder deadlines — and the Executive Director sees everything consolidated in one clean dashboard. The ED can generate one of two report templates on demand (board or funder), each covering program outcomes, fundraising progress, and upcoming deadlines, with a short ED narrative field. No spreadsheet required.

---

## 2. Users & Scale

| Role | Description |
|---|---|
| **Executive Director** | Reads the dashboard; generates board and funder reports. Uses it monthly for board meetings, weekly when a funder report is due, and ad-hoc for new grant opportunities. Full read access to all data. |
| **Head of Fundraising** | Manages funder records, revenue entries, and the funder deadline calendar. Can generate and export funder reports. Uses it weekly. Read access to program outcomes; write access to funders, revenue, and report generation. |
| **Program staff** | Enter outcome metric data for their assigned program only, monthly or after events. No access to other programs, revenue, or funders. |
| **Admin (builder)** | Configures programs, metrics, targets, and users. Not an org staff role — this is the person building and maintaining the tool. |
| **Scale (hard)** | ~2 primary users (ED, Head of Fundraising), up to ~10 program staff. Single organization, single instance. No multi-tenant architecture. |
| **Device assumption** | Web browser on laptop or desktop. Mobile-responsive is sufficient; no native app. |
| **Data volume** | 3–10 programs, 5–20 metrics each, monthly entries. Well within a lightweight database. |

---

## 3. User Story

> As the Executive Director, I want to open a single tool and immediately see how all our programs are performing against their Theory of Change targets, where our fundraising stands, and which funder deadlines are coming up — so I can generate an accurate board or funder report in under 30 minutes, without chasing data across multiple systems.

---

## 4. Walkthrough (Step by Step)

### Flow A — ED: Monthly Board Report

1. ED logs in and lands on the dashboard.
2. Dashboard shows: program outcome metrics (actual vs. target), fundraising revenue vs. goal, and upcoming funder deadlines. Off-track items are flagged in red.
3. ED clicks "Generate Report" and selects **Board Report** and a reporting period (e.g. May 2026).
4. A report preview appears. ED fills in the optional "ED Notes" field (free text, max ~300 words).
5. ED exports as PDF or prints. Report is clean enough to hand directly to a board member.
6. **Error path:** If any program has missing data for the selected period, the report shows "No data entered" in that cell — never blank, never zero.

### Flow B — ED or Head of Fundraising: Funder Report

1. ED or Head of Fundraising identifies an upcoming funder deadline on the dashboard or funder list.
2. Either user navigates to `/report`, selects **Funder Report**, selects the relevant funder and reporting period.
3. Report pre-populates with data for the program(s) linked to that funder only — not all programs.
4. User fills in the optional "ED Notes" field.
5. User exports as PDF.
6. **Error path:** If the selected funder has no linked programs, the system blocks export and prompts the user to link at least one program first.

### Flow C — Head of Fundraising: Revenue Entry & Funder Management

1. Head of Fundraising logs in and navigates to `/revenue` or `/funders`.
2. On `/revenue`: two distinct actions are available — (a) enter an actual revenue amount for a funder/category and period; (b) set or update a revenue target for a funder/category, which creates a new `revenue_targets` row with an `effective_from` date. These are separate operations in the UI. Actuals and targets are not entered on the same form row.
3. A previously submitted revenue entry can be edited by the Head of Fundraising at any time. Edits overwrite the previous value; the system logs `updated_by` and `updated_at` on the record.
4. On `/funders`: creates or edits a funder record (name, grant amount, renewal date, report due date, status, linked programs).
5. Changes are immediately reflected on the ED dashboard.
6. **Error path:** Submitting a revenue entry with no period selected is blocked with a field-level error.

### Flow D — Admin: System Configuration

1. Admin logs into `/admin`.
2. **Programs:** Creates a program (name, description, active/inactive). Editing a program name does not delete historical entries.
3. **Metrics:** For each program, adds a metric (name, unit, target period, off-track threshold) and an initial target value with an `effective_from` date in a single atomic operation — both records are created together or neither is. The admin UI must not allow a metric to be saved without a corresponding initial `metric_targets` row. This is enforced at the application layer; the database should also enforce it if the stack supports deferrable foreign key constraints. Deleting a metric is blocked if it has existing entries — admin must deactivate instead.
4. **Users:** Creates a user (email, password, role). For staff role, assigns exactly one program. Role cannot be changed after creation without explicit confirmation step.
5. **Targets:** Creates a new `metric_targets` row with an `effective_from` date. Previous targets are preserved — historical periods continue to use the target that was in effect at the time. Targets cannot be backdated to a period that already has entries.
6. **Error path:** Creating a staff user without assigning a program is blocked. Creating a metric without a target value is blocked.

### Flow E — Staff: Program Data Entry

1. Staff member logs in and is taken directly to their program's entry form — no other navigation available.
2. Enters metric values for the current period.
3. Submits. Data is immediately visible on the ED dashboard.
4. **Error path:** Leaving a required metric field blank blocks submission with a field-level error. Staff cannot edit a previously submitted entry — they must contact admin.

