## 9. Database Schema

The following tables are required. Field-level types TBD by the coding agent based on stack; structure and relationships are fixed.

### programs
| Field | Description |
|---|---|
| id | Primary key |
| name | Program name (e.g. "Employment Support") |
| description | Short text |
| is_active | Boolean — inactive programs are hidden from entry forms but historical data is preserved |

### metrics
| Field | Description |
|---|---|
| id | Primary key |
| program_id | Foreign key → programs |
| name | Metric name (e.g. "Clients served") |
| unit | Unit label (e.g. "people", "%", "$") |
| target_period | Enum: monthly \| annual |
| off_track_threshold | Decimal (0–1). Metric is off-track when actual < target × threshold. Default: 0.80 |
| is_active | Boolean — deactivated instead of deleted when entries exist |

> **Design decision (resolves OQ-3):** Target values are stored in a separate `metric_targets` table, not on `metrics`. This means targets are versioned by effective date — a target updated in July does not overwrite the target that applied in March. Historical reporting is always accurate to the target that was in effect at the time. This is the correct default regardless of whether targets change mid-year.

### metric_targets
| Field | Description |
|---|---|
| id | Primary key |
| metric_id | Foreign key → metrics |
| target_value | Numeric target |
| effective_from | Date — this target applies from this date forward |
| set_by | Foreign key → users (admin only) |
| set_at | Timestamp |

> When evaluating a metric for a given period, the system uses the `metric_targets` row with the latest `effective_from` date that is on or before the period start date.

### metric_entries
| Field | Description |
|---|---|
| id | Primary key |
| metric_id | Foreign key → metrics |
| period | Date — stored as first day of month (e.g. 2026-06-01) |
| actual_value | Numeric |
| entered_by | Foreign key → users |
| entered_at | Timestamp |

### funders
| Field | Description |
|---|---|
| id | Primary key |
| name | Funder organization name |
| grant_amount | Numeric |
| status | Enum: active \| prospect \| lapsed |
| renewal_date | Date |
| report_due_date | Date |
| notes | Free text |

### funder_programs
| Field | Description |
|---|---|
| funder_id | Foreign key → funders |
| program_id | Foreign key → programs |

### revenue_targets

> **Design decision:** Revenue targets are versioned separately from actuals, mirroring the `metric_targets` approach. The Head of Fundraising sets an annual or monthly revenue target per funder (or category), and that target is looked up at report time using the same effective-date logic as metric targets. Monthly `revenue_entries` rows carry only actuals.

| Field | Description |
|---|---|
| id | Primary key |
| funder_id | Foreign key → funders (nullable for general donation targets) |
| category | Enum: grant \| donation \| other |
| target_amount | Numeric |
| target_period | Enum: monthly \| annual |
| effective_from | Date — this target applies from this date forward |
| set_by | Foreign key → users |
| set_at | Timestamp |

> When evaluating revenue for a given period, the system uses the `revenue_targets` row with the latest `effective_from` date that is on or before the period start date, matching on funder_id and category.

### revenue_entries
| Field | Description |
|---|---|
| id | Primary key |
| funder_id | Foreign key → funders (nullable for general donations) |
| category | Enum: grant \| donation \| other |
| period | Date — stored as first day of month |
| actual_amount | Numeric |
| entered_by | Foreign key → users |
| entered_at | Timestamp |
| updated_by | Foreign key → users — null if never edited after initial entry |
| updated_at | Timestamp — null if never edited after initial entry |

### users
| Field | Description |
|---|---|
| id | Primary key |
| email | Login identifier |
| password_hash | bcrypt hash — never plaintext |
| role | Enum: ed \| fundraising \| staff \| admin |
| program_id | Foreign key → programs — required when role = staff, null otherwise |

